Wildcard Central Bank Governor?
Prague—Recently, there has been one-sided criticism of central banks in developed countries.
The main criticisms center on this: since 2008, monetary policymakers have been too active, expanding their powers too rapidly, and endangering the economy.
This claim — strange as it is, gaining popularity among ideological camps that should be irreconcilable, such as liberals and neo-Marxists — is entirely wrong.
Critics fail to understand that modern central banks are responsible not only for combating inflation but also for maintaining long-term price stability.
Price levels are akin to body temperature, fluctuating within a range that is neither too high nor too low without causing serious symptoms.
In fighting deflation caused by weak demand and containing high inflation driven by excessive demand, central banks must be equally "active."
Although the battle is entirely symmetrical, public assessment of it is inexplicably skewed, especially in countries where people are financially very conservative.
This includes my home country, the Czech Republic. Czech savers have very small savings, and the loan-to-deposit ratio is still far below 100%.
Czechs remain concerned about inflation, even though the inflation rate last year reached its lowest point in 13 years, and the National Bank of Czech Republic, which I have been deputy governor of since 2013, has been working to eliminate deflation risks.
One common complaint about central bank policies since 2008 is that they have caused redistribution effects.
Of course it would, but so what?
Any monetary policy action will reallocate wealth.
Raising interest rates pleases savers, while cutting rates benefits borrowers.
Importers prefer strong exchange rates; exporters prefer weak exchange rates.
For monetary policy to be effective, it must have different impacts on different groups at different times.
This is not a mistake; this is the essence of monetary policy.
Some critics also argue that central banks have failed to meet inflation targets, making their activism not only unnecessary but also ineffective.
Sometimes they even combine these contradictory criticisms in one sentence, as if they were blaming someone for causing casualties while firing blanks.
The reality is that central banks around the world have succeeded – and spectacularly so – in maintaining price stability and monetary purchasing power during and after the global financial crisis.
If not for their intervention, their economy would have faced catastrophic deflation, a dramatic plunge in asset prices, and a complete collapse of both financial and real sectors.
Clearly, strong action was the right approach to address the crisis (whether central banks played the right role during the outbreak of the financial crisis is a different issue).
In a system using non-intrinsic-value elastic currency, monetary purchasing power can be roughly maintained only if the money supply changes over time.
Therefore, price stability, rather than the quantity of money, is the key issue.
The expansion of central bank balance sheets reflects the depth of the problems faced by many economies after 2008.
In this context, central banks took necessary measures to maintain purchasing power and price stability.
For them, there is no "activism"; only the mission to be permanently fulfilled.
If you find this assertion arrogant, let me provide some evidence.
People vote with their wallets.
If their purchasing power declined significantly after 2008, they would naturally seek to swap their currency for others (such as precious metals or other savings methods).
This is rare in the developed world.
Of course, many central banks did not meet their inflation targets.
(Central banks typically define the ideal "economic temperature" as an annual inflation rate of around 2%. )
) But this, while unpleasant, does not lead to disaster, especially considering that some price declines stem from supply - rather than demand - shocks, such as plummeting oil prices.
This shock benefits consumers and poses no threat to price stability, at least for net oil importers.
Consider this scenario.
The company plans to increase sales by 2%, but the managers achieve this by increasing sales by 1% each year for two consecutive years.
Would you think this company fails?
Probably not.
After all, private companies' planned profits and revenues often deviate by more than 10% from actual figures.
Most business operating environment variables are fewer than those of central banks.
How can you expect central banks to always hit precise inflation targets regardless of the economic environment?
It must be clarified that I did not say that central banks should not strive to work towards their goals.
They should absolutely do so.
Moreover, they should also absolutely not allow inflation expectations to become unstable.
But, when evaluating central banks, people need to maintain appropriate discretion.
They indeed need to stop saying things that are not true, such as the central bank's policy arsenal not only being depleted but also nearing depletion.
Monetary policymakers have ample weapons and unlimited ammunition at their disposal.
These weapons come in different calibers and have varying degrees of effectiveness at different times.
Not all weapons are suitable for all economies in all circumstances.
But the central bank's ability to create and destroy money is theoretically unlimited.
Central bank governors should say "enough" to the ignorant criticism they face.
Our critics cannot explain in a clear and credible manner why price stability is an incorrect goal, what key objectives the central bank should pursue instead, or what fundamentally different approach they should have taken since 2008.
There is a simple reason for this: the approach taken by central banks in developed countries since the crisis was the correct one.
In fact, this approach pulled our economy back from the brink.
You're welcome.
